article.headline: Arizona State 68, Washington State 62
article.story: TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Serge Angounou picked the right time to be perfect. Angounou scored 18 points on 7-of-7 shooting from the field and 4-for-4 from the free throw line and also grabbed 10 rebounds to lead Arizona State past Washington State 68-62 Thursday night. "Tonight was not a good night because I didn't stop (Jeff) Varem on time like I was supposed to," Angounou said of the Cougars' leading scorer. "It was not a very good night but we won." Angounou, who has five double-doubles this season, made two free throws with 32 seconds left to give the Sun Devils (15-5, 4-4 Pac-10) an eight-point lead and secure the win after Washington State got within four. Varem had a career-high 24 points for Washington State (8-9, 3-5), which has lost three in a low. "We don't have the kind of quickness and size where we can get out and get after people," said Washington State coach Dick Bennett. "We've got to protect the lane first and then try to get out on shooters." Kevin Kruger added 14 points on 4-for-6 shooting from the 3-point line and Bryson Krueger had 13 points for Arizona State, while Ike Diogu had 15 points and 13 rebounds -- his conference-leading 10th double-double this season -- before fouling out with 33 seconds left. After Angounou's free throws, Robbie Cowgill got the Cougars within 66-60 and Thomas Kelati, who had 17 points and nine rebounds, stole the ensuing inbounds pass and Varem scored a layup to cut the lead to 66-62. But Washington State got no closer. Arizona State led 33-23 at halftime before the Cougars ran off 10 straight points to get within 42-39 with 12:45 left. "Washington State is a difficult team to guard, but I was pleased with our zone and man-to-man defense tonight," said Arizona State coach Rob Evans. The Cougars hurt themselves by missing nine of their first 13 free throws. "I'll take 110 percent of the blame," said Kelati, an 81 percent free throw shooter this season who missed 5-of-7 from the line. "It's my senior year and I have hit free throws so well for my entire career. To not convert, especially down the stretch, is uncharacteristic of me. I let my team down tonight by not converting on those free throws." Diogu has scored in double figures for all 79 games of his career and has 25 double-doubles as a Sun Devil. "There were still some lapses today," Diogu said. "We built up a 13-point lead on them and then we squandered it away again. So we are definitely getting there but we are not where we need to be." It was the first Arizona State win over Washington State since 2003. The Sun Devils made 22 of 46 from the field against the best defense in the conference, which had held opponents to 54.6 points and 38.5 percent shooting coming into the game.
